#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:1
# header
msgid "# Code of Conduct Committee Governance "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:3
# header
msgid "## Membership"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:5
msgid "Any voting member of the Carpentries community, as defined in The Carpentries bylaws, may express their interest to volunteer to sit on the [Code of Conduct Committee (CoCc)](https://carpentries.org/coc-ctte/) (the Committee). \n"
"The Committee will onboard its members on a yearly basis through open calls and from available volunteers. \n"
"The Executive Council (EC) will be notified about any new members. \n"
"New members will undergo an application and onboarding process before they are officially seated on the Committee."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:10
# header
msgid "## Onboarding and training"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:12
msgid "The onboarding process is determined by the Committee, and the EC will be notified about this process.\n"
"New members are not immediately seated on the Committee, and thus not included in issue resolution, until after onboarding is completed. "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:15
msgid "The current onboarding process involves reading assignments in [The Carpentries Code of Conduct documents](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/policies/index_coc.html) and selected chapters from [How to respond to Code of Conduct Reports](https://files.frameshiftconsulting.com/books/cocguide.pdf)\n"
"(by Valerie Aurora, based on a short guide written by Mary Gardiner). \n"
"Additionally, incident response training will be organised for the new and existing members to ensure they can confidently serve on the committee."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:19
# header
msgid "## Administration"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:21
msgid "The Committee consists of a minimum of five members; approximately 10 is recommended. \n"
"The Committee, in addition, has a liaison from the Carpentries Core Team and a liaison from the EC. \n"
"The liaisons have the responsibility of informing the CoCc of anything that is relevant from their respective groups. \n"
"They are also responsible for conveying issues and updates to their respective groups from the CoCc that are relevant for them while respecting the confidentiality requirements of the Committee."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:26
msgid "The Committee has two chairs - a Governance Chair and an Incident Response Chair. \n"
"These individuals are responsible for guiding the Committee’s work. "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:29
# header
msgid "## Voting"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:31
msgid "The CoCc participates in two types of voting - votes about incidents and those not about incidents (e.g. business, policy, administrative matters). "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:33
# header
msgid "### Non-incident voting"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:35
msgid "For non-incident related matters, the Committee passes votes with a simple majority of the non-liaison members, with the Governance Chair breaking any ties. \n"
"The Carpentries Core Team and Executive Council liaisons do not vote on motions, but are welcome to provide feedback and insight.  \n"
"Quorum in meetings is more than 50% of the non-liaison CoCc members. "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:39
# header
msgid "### Incident voting"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:41
msgid "For incident related matters, the liaisons to the CoCc will abstain from voting, unless their vote is needed to ensure that an incident or other need can be responded to in a timely manner according to the [Incident Response Guidelines](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/policies/incident-response.html). \n"
"The Incidence Response Lead of the [Incident Response group](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/policies/enforcement-guidelines.html#incident-response-assessment) will make this decision and indicate that a liaison vote will be necessary to resolve the incident."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:44
msgid "Should the Executive Council liaison participate in a CoCc vote, and that resolution is appealed before the Executive Council, the liaison member will abstain from that appeal vote."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:46
# header
msgid "## Terms of office"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:48
msgid "The expected term of office for each Committee member is one to three years, however, members may remain longer if continuity of the Committee is a concern. \n"
"During their time on the Committee, members may temporarily withdraw from Committee work for up to 3 months provided they inform the Governance Chair in writing. \n"
"If the members are unavailable for longer than 3 months, they will be asked to take a leave from the Committee. \n"
"They may volunteer to rejoin when they are available again following the onboarding procedure described earlier in the document. \n"
"This will allow us to maintain privacy for the reports that will be handled in their absence and create an opportunity for new members to join the Committee."
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:54
msgid "The Chairs are expected to sit for approximately one year. \n"
"New Chairs are selected from among those who have been on the Committee for at least one year. One of the available members can volunteer to be elected to take on the role of a Chair. "
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:57
# header
msgid "## Main duties of the position holders"
msgstr ""

#: topic_folders/policies/coc-governance.md:59
msgid "All members of the CoCc must read, understand and abide by the [membership agreement](https://docs.carpentries.org/topic_folders/policies/coc-membership-agreement.html#). \n"
